{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624436"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:18:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:18:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16900"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16900"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76355"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9590"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1247"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10742"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22651"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76355"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA genetic counsellor is discussing chromosomal disorders with medical students. The discussion focuses on conditions resulting from the presence of additional chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the chromosomal abnormality and common clinical features of Patau syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trisomy X with tall stature and learning difficulties","Trisomy 13 with holoprosencephaly, polydactyly, and heart defects","Trisomy 21 with flat facial features and single palmar crease","Monosomy X with webbed neck and lymphoedema","Trisomy 18 with rocker-bottom feet and clenched fists"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy 13 with holoprosencephaly, polydactyly, and heart defects\u003C/strong\u003E describes Patau syndrome. This condition results from having three copies of chromosome 13 instead of the normal two copies. The extra chromosome typically arises from nondisjunction during meiosis I.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options describe other chromosomal conditions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy 18 with rocker-bottom feet and clenched fists\u003C/strong\u003E describes Edwards syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy 21 with flat facial features and single palmar crease\u003C/strong\u003E describes Down syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonosomy X with webbed neck and lymphoedema\u003C/strong\u003E describes Turner syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy X with tall stature and learning difficulties\u003C/strong\u003E describes Triple X syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatau syndrome has a characteristic triad of central nervous system malformations (particularly holoprosencephaly), polydactyly (extra digits), and congenital heart defects. Additional features may include cleft lip/palate, microphthalmia, and severe developmental delay.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patau syndrome (trisomy 13) results from the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 13.","Key clinical features of Patau syndrome include holoprosencephaly, polydactyly, and congenital heart defects.","Most cases of Patau syndrome occur due to nondisjunction during meiosis I in the formation of gametes."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16900"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T09:14:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T09:46:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9590"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76355"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api